              line-height: 1.5;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Markets tank</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Summary: Markets plunged on Monday, and Wall Street experienced other losses due to Trump's sweeping tariffs.</strong></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Asian markets yesterday slumped after the sweeping tariffs were announced. Japan’s Nikkei 225 and Taiwan’s Taiex hit the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-08-04-2025-h3-5-circuit-breaker" target="_blank">circuit breaker</a>, which paused trading when their future products were poised for an 8% and 10% decline, respectively. Shares of TSMC and Foxconn declined 10%.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The trend continued westward to Singapore, South Korea, and Hong Kong, with each losing 8.5%, 4.8%, and 9.28%. Meanwhile, China saw the Shanghai Composite shed 4.21%. The bloodbath continued in Europe and Australia as well. The US market showed no signs of revival. S&P 500 futures slid 4.31% in volatile trading, while Nasdaq futures dived 5.45%, pulled down by Apple given its heavy reliance on Chinese manufacturing.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Goldman Sachs's <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-08-04-2025-h3-6-recent-forecast" target="_blank">recent forecast</a> predicts a 45% probability of a US recession in the next 12 months. In his annual letter to shareholders, JPMorgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon claimed that the tariffs would increase inflation and the probability of a recession.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Despite slow growth, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell assured the economy is in a good place, adding that the tariffs will raise consumer spending.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
